1. Signature
Number.isInteger(value) -> Boolean
Parameter: value (any type)

2. Behavior and result criteria
- Returns true if typeof value === 'number' and value is finite and the mathematical value is an integer (no fractional part). Equivalent to: isFinite(value) && Math.floor(value) === value when typeof value is 'number'.
- It does not coerce non-number types. e.g., Number.isInteger('3') -> false.

3. Polyfill and implementation notes
Polyfill (conceptual):
  function isInteger(value) {
    return typeof value === 'number' && isFinite(value) && Math.floor(value) === value;
  }
Edge cases: NaN, Infinity, -Infinity -> all return false.

4. Use in validation and numeric checks
- Use Number.isInteger to guard functions that require integer inputs (array indices, bit widths, code unit indices) to prevent silent coercion and hard-to-find bugs.

